    <section id="what-is" class="content-section">
      <h2>What is Feline Hypertension?</h2>
      <p>High blood pressure (hypertension) in cats causes ongoing, often silent damage to the kidneys, eyes, heart, and brain. It is extremely common in cats with CKD or hyperthyroidism — two conditions that frequently drive blood pressure up — and it is frequently undertreated because it isn't always checked routinely.</p>
      <p>Yams had hypertension alongside his CKD. Sorbet is currently managed for it alongside his other conditions.</p>
      <div class="content-callout content-callout--urgent">
        <strong>A hypertensive crisis can cause sudden blindness.</strong> If your cat suddenly seems unable to see — bumping into things, dilated fixed pupils — this is an emergency. Go to a vet immediately. Caught early, some vision loss can be reversed. Left untreated, it typically cannot.
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="monitoring" class="content-section">
      <h2>Why Blood Pressure Should Be Checked Regularly</h2>
      <p>Cats are notoriously difficult to get accurate blood pressure readings from due to "white coat hypertension" — stress at the vet inflates the numbers. Multiple readings over time, ideally taken when the cat is calm, give a more accurate picture.</p>
      <p>The target is generally below 160 mmHg systolic. Values consistently above 180 mmHg indicate severe hypertension requiring immediate treatment.</p>
      <div class="content-callout">
        <strong>Ask at every appointment:</strong> "Has blood pressure been checked today?" If your cat has CKD, hyperthyroidism, or heart disease, blood pressure monitoring should be part of routine care — not an occasional add-on.
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="treatment" class="content-section">
      <h2>Treatment</h2>
      <div class="meds-list">
        <div class="med-item">
          <div class="med-name">Telmisartan (Semintra)</div>
          <div class="med-desc">First-line treatment for hypertension in cats in the US and Canada. An angiotensin receptor blocker (ARB) that lowers blood pressure and also reduces protein in urine — which helps slow kidney disease progression. Available as an oral solution. Sorbet is currently on this.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="med-item">
          <div class="med-name">Amlodipine</div>
          <div class="med-desc">Calcium channel blocker, very effective at lowering blood pressure. Often used when telmisartan alone isn't achieving the target, or when telmisartan isn't tolerated. Does not have the kidney-protective protein-reducing effect of telmisartan.</div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="vet-questions" class="content-section">
      <h2>Questions to Ask Your Vet</h2>
      <ul class="vet-questions">
        <li>When was blood pressure last measured, and what was the reading?</li>
        <li>Given my cat's CKD / hyperthyroidism, should we be monitoring blood pressure more frequently?</li>
        <li>Is my cat on the right medication, and is the current dose achieving the target?</li>
        <li>Is there protein in the urine? Should we use telmisartan specifically for its kidney-protective properties?</li>
        <li>What signs of hypertensive damage should I watch for at home?</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

